n of white cities like Fargo in ways that complicate their demographics. Race-ing Fargo shows that race, religion, and decorum prove to be powerful forces determining worthiness and belonging in the city and draws attention to the different roles that state and private sectors played in shaping ideas about race and citizenship on a local level. Through the comparative study of white secular Muslim Bosnians and Black Christian Southern Sudanese, Race-ing Fargo demonstrates how cross-cultural and transnational understandings of race, ethnicity, class, and religion shape daily citizenship practices and belonging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralismzNorth DakotazFargo. 0aPlace (Philosophy)xSocial aspectszNorth DakotazFargo. 0aRace awarenesszNorth DakotazFargo. 0aRacexSocial aspectszNorth DakotazFargo. 0aRefugeeszNorth DakotazFargo. 0aSocial integrationzNorth DakotazFargo. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aCritical race studies, urban anthropology, citizenship studies, ethnic studies, feminist studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501751141?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501751141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docume